<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12069j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12069j">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12069j"> 69(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Aber = bay ~</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Il est certain que la baie du Mont Saint-Michel, limit&eacute;e par le cap Lihou (Granville) et le Groin de Cancale, est plus bretonne que normande | par l&apos;&eacute;tendue de ses c&ocirc;tes, la nature de ses falaises et sa configuration g&eacute;n&eacute;rale; il ne lui manque que la profondeur de ses eaux pour &ecirc;tre tout &agrave; fait un <mark>aber</mark> armoricain. / Les Normands eux-m&ecirc;mes, si fiers de poss&eacute;der sur leur terre-marine &mdash; (ce mot est du trouv&egrave;re Wace) &mdash; la huiti&egrave;me merveille du monde, ont reconnu, de vieille date, que la baie appartient plus &agrave; la Bretagne qu&apos;&agrave; leur propre province. <br><font color="green">[It is certain that the bay of Mont Saint-Michel, between cape Lihou (Granville) and Groin de Cancale, is more Breton than Normand by the extent of its coast, the nature of its rock-faces and the general configuration; it only lacks water depth in order to be altogether an Armorican &lsquo;<mark>aber</mark>&rsquo;. The Normans themselves, so proud to have on their marine land (the expression was coined by the troubadour Wace) the eighth wonder of the world, have long realized that the bay belongs more to the Bretons than to their own province.]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="SMIN" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SMIN"><cite title="source">Le Mont Saint-Michel Inconnu</cite></a> (1912) 284-5</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Breton <i>aber</i>: rivermouth; otherwise, a narrow valley influxed by the sea. </mm> </dd></dl>
